<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO ED</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jan 13  6:57:19 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Ed,<br><br>
Right on. You don't have to explain anything to me.<br><br>
You said in an earlier post that you were honored to walk in the company of fellow vets, I feel the same.<br><br>
My first night in the field, our 81mm platoon dropped a short round that killed one man and wounded another two. It was a routine Defensive Target, so the excuse of the &quot;fog of battle&quot; didn't apply. Elevation was 1556 mils. It was a major screw up that was not easily forgotten by the rifle platoons. They were very reluctant to call in fire missions, and showed a general resentment towards us in mortars.<br><br>
The first thing I did the next day, when all the brass came out to look at the situation was to make up my mind that an accident like that would not happen again. It didn't. And with a few changes in SOP we became a better and safer unit.<br><br>
The decorations I received mean alot to me, because they remind me of the valuable lessons I learned while serving in VN - and my refusal to give up by believing the negative words of others directed towards the mortar platoon. It would have been easy for a 21 year old to do that.<br><br>
Someone mentioned that medals represent who they are. Don't know how that statement was meant, but I will say that they represent the triumph of the human spirit (mine and the 6 men I led who received Bronze with &quot;V's&quot;) over a difficult situation. Sound like bragging? I don't have time to listen, I'm too busy with present day challenges. I still haven't given up on life and gladly face what each day has to present.<br><br>
Funny, the Battalion Sergeant Major Pike pointed to my decoration and told me the one about taking it and 25 cents and buying a cup of coffee with it. I didn't pay any attention to that either.
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


